The recipe covers all required topics:[0m[0m
[0m[0m
- **The Problem:** Denial rates (10-15%), rework costs ($25-118), the value of pre-submission prediction, and the provider-vs-payer framing distinction[0m[0m
- **The Technology:** Gradient-boosted trees (XGBoost/LightGBM) as the primary model, with logistic regression and random forest baselines; why tabular models beat deep learning here; SHAP explainability as a non-negotiable requirement; explicit framing as supervised classification (not clustering)[0m[0m
- **Features:** CPT/HCPCS, ICD-10, diagnosis-procedure pairs, payer ID and payer-specific denial rates, provider type and historical denial rates, place of service, PA status, claim amount, modifiers, patient demographics, coverage details[0m[0m
- **Three lifecycle prediction points:** Pre-visit (eligibility/PA risk), pre-billing (coding errors), post-submission (payer behavior)[0m[0m
- **General architecture + AWS implementation:** SageMaker training and hosting, Glue feature pipeline, DynamoDB prediction store, Lambda worklist engine, batch and real-time scoring paths[0m[0m
- **Pseudocode walkthrough:** 4 steps covering feature engineering, model training with class imbalance handling, real-time scoring with SHAP explanations, and worklist generation[0m[0m
- **The Honest Take:** Class imbalance, bias risks from learning inappropriate denial patterns, payer rule drift, the intervention-success feedback loop problem, precision-recall tradeoffs, and regulatory/fairness considerations[0m[0m
- **Variations:** Payer-specific ensembles, multi-class denial reason prediction, appeal success prediction[0m[0m
- **Related Recipes:** Links to 7.1, 7.2, 1.4, 1.5, and 3.3[0m[0m
- **Navigation:** Previous (7.10), chapter index, next (Chapter 8)[0m[0m
